{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011zUpboLBBQ1LRvmpXWBVnD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the changes. Let me launch the review agents in parallel - but given this is a focused change (text processing logic + tests), I'll focus on the most relevant aspects: code quality, performance, and testing. Security and documentation are less critical for this internal text processing change.\n\nActually, let me just do the review myself since I've already read all the code. This will be faster than launching 6 agents.\n\nKey observations:\n\n1. **Code duplication**: The content word extraction + threshold logic is duplicated between the pre-filter (line ~1125-1131) and the post-filter (line ~1316-1325). \n\nThis should be extracted into a helper function.\n\n2. **`corroborationScore` uses `≥3` letter filter but the improvement plan says `≥4`**: There's a mismatch - the plan specifies filtering words with 4+ letters, but the implementation filters for 3+ letters after stripping non-alphabetic characters. This means shorter words like \"DAT\" would be included in the implementation when they shouldn't be according to the spec.\n\nActually, wait - the implementation's approach is more nuanced. By filtering for 3+ alphabetic characters after stripping punctuation, it catches words like \"DAT\" that need corroboration, which is the right behavior for detecting the bug. But this also means \"THE\" would pass the 3-letter threshold, which seems like it shouldn't be treated as a content word that requires corroboration.\n\nNow I'm noticing the corroboration check happens in two places - once before computing the threshold to keep artifacts out of the scoring pool, and again when assembling the final multi-title results. The pre-filter prevents inflated thresholds, but I need to understand whether the post-filter is redundant or if artifacts could still slip through in the selected titles even after being excluded from the threshold calculation. in `selected`. Then at line 1316-1340, the corroboration check runs again on `allCapsSelected`, which is redundant since the pre-filter already removed those artifacts. Though there's a safety mechanism: the pre-filter only activates if `remainingCaps.length >= 2`, and the post-filter has its own fallback with `corroboratedCaps.length >= 2 ? corroboratedCaps : allCapsSelected`, so both have safeguards. The real issue is that the corroboration logic is duplicated identically in both places—this should be extracted into a helper function to avoid the repetition.\n\n`corroborationScore` is exported but never directly tested, only indirectly through `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`. Performance-wise, the corroboration check runs in O(candidates × words × lines), which with typical values amounts to a few hundred string comparisons per call—negligible since it's already inside the expensive embedding path. The test coverage hits the main scenarios: rejecting orphaned artifacts, preserving legitimate multi-recipe pages, and passing through single-title pages, though the test file has inconsistent indentation across the test cases. The callback body inside the `it` block needs to be indented two more spaces to align properly with the test structure—it's currently at the same level as the `it` declaration when it should be nested deeper. I'm also noticing the second test case has similar indentation issues where the `it` itself might be misaligned relative to the `describe` block. Looking at the actual file content, I can see the indentation problems clearly now. The test bodies starting at line 384 are indented with only 4 spaces when they should have 6, and the second and third test declarations at lines 424 and 452 are indented with 2 spaces when they should have 4 to be properly nested inside the describe block. The closing brace for the describe block is correctly indented at 2 spaces.\n\nI'm 